NOTES_2PETER = {
    1: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Symeon" (Συμεών) preserves the Hebrew form of Simon, a Semitic spelling found also in Acts 15:14, lending authenticity to Petrine authorship. "Isotimon" (ἰσότιμον, Strong\'s G2472) is a hapax legomenon in the NT meaning "of equal honor/value," emphasizing that Gentile believers possess a faith no less precious than that of the apostles. THEOLOGICAL: "Our God and Savior Jesus Christ" (τοῦ θεοῦ ἡμῶν καὶ σωτῆρος Ἰησοῦ Χριστοῦ) follows the Granville Sharp rule: a single article governing two nouns joined by "kai" with the same case refers to one person—thus directly identifying Jesus Christ as God and Savior (cf. Titus 2:13).',
        2: 'GREEK: "Epignōsis" (ἐπίγνωσις, Strong\'s G1922) is intensified "gnōsis"—not mere knowledge but full, experiential, relational knowledge. Peter uses this term four times in this chapter (vv. 2, 3, 8, cf. v. 20), making it a programmatic keyword. Grace and peace are multiplied not through ritual but through deepening knowledge of God and Jesus the Lord.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: "His divine power" (τῆς θείας δυνάμεως αὐτοῦ) indicates that everything necessary for spiritual life and godliness has already been granted—a completed gift (perfect participle δεδωρημένης). GREEK: "Theios" (θεῖος, Strong\'s G2304) meaning "divine" appears in the NT only here, v. 4, and Acts 17:29, showing Peter engaging Hellenistic vocabulary to communicate transcendent realities. "Aretē" (ἀρετή) here means "moral excellence" or "manifested power," echoing LXX usage for God\'s mighty deeds (Isa 42:12).',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Partakers of the divine nature" (θείας κοινωνοὶ φύσεως) is one of the most remarkable statements in the NT—believers participate in God\'s own nature through His promises. This is not pantheistic absorption but covenantal transformation. GREEK: "Apophygontes" (ἀποφυγόντες, Strong\'s G668) means "having escaped," an aorist participle indicating a decisive break from the world\'s corruption. "Phthora" (φθορά) denotes decay and moral ruin, the opposite of divine incorruptibility (cf. 2 Pet 2:12, 19).',
        9: 'GREEK: "Myōpazōn" (μυωπάζων, Strong\'s G3467) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "being short-sighted" or "squinting"—one who can see only what is near but not the far-reaching realities of salvation. Combined with "blind" (τυφλός), Peter describes a progressive spiritual dysfunction. THEOLOGICAL: Forgetting one\'s cleansing from former sins produces moral blindness; sanctification requires active remembrance of justification (cf. Rom 6:1-11).',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: The "eternal kingdom of our Lord and Savior Jesus Christ" (τὴν αἰώνιον βασιλείαν τοῦ κυρίου ἡμῶν καὶ σωτῆρος Ἰησοῦ Χριστοῦ) again applies the Granville Sharp construction, identifying Jesus as both Lord and Savior who reigns over an everlasting dominion. TYPOLOGY: "Entrance" (εἴσοδος) echoes Israel\'s entry into the Promised Land; as Joshua led Israel in, so Jesus the true Joshua leads believers into the eternal kingdom (cf. Heb 4:8-11). The adverb "richly" (πλουσίως) suggests not bare entry but an abundant, triumphant welcome.',
        16: 'GREEK: "Epoptai" (ἐπόπται, Strong\'s G2030) means "eyewitnesses" but carries the connotation of initiated observers in Greek mystery religions—Peter repurposes this term to assert that the apostles witnessed no fabricated myth but real divine disclosure. "Sesophismenois mythois" (σεσοφισμένοις μύθοις) means "cleverly devised myths," contrasting pagan fabrications with apostolic testimony. HISTORICAL: Peter references the Transfiguration (Matt 17:1-8; Mark 9:2-8; Luke 9:28-36) as empirical verification of Christ\'s divine majesty and future parousia.',
        17: 'TYPOLOGY: The divine voice echoes the baptism of Jesus (Matt 3:17) and recalls Psalm 2:7 ("You are My Son") and Isaiah 42:1 ("My Chosen One in whom My soul delights"), uniting royal Messianic sonship with the Suffering Servant identity. GREEK: "Megaloprepous doxēs" (μεγαλοπρεποῦς δόξης, "Majestic Glory") is a circumlocution for God\'s manifest presence—"megaloprepēs" (Strong\'s G3169) is a NT hapax, meaning "befitting greatness." This recalls the kavod (כָּבוֹד) of YHWH descending in theophanic cloud, as at Sinai and the Tabernacle (Exod 24:16-17).',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: The prophetic word is "made more sure" (βεβαιότερον)—the Transfiguration confirmed what the prophets foretold, not replacing Scripture but corroborating it. GREEK: "Phōsphoros" (φωσφόρος, Strong\'s G5459), literally "light-bearer," refers to the morning star (Venus), a Messianic title (cf. Rev 22:16; Num 24:17). "Auchmēros" (αὐχμηρός, Strong\'s G850) is a NT hapax meaning "dry, murky, squalid"—depicting the present age as a dark, parched place awaiting the dawn of Christ\'s return. TYPOLOGY: The lamp in darkness echoes Psalm 119:105 and anticipates the eschatological dawn when Christ, the Morning Star, illumines believers\' hearts fully.',
        21: 'THEOLOGICAL: Prophecy originates not from human will but from the Holy Spirit who "carried" (φερόμενοι, pheromenoi) the prophets—the same verb used of a ship driven by wind (Acts 27:15, 17). This affirms divine inspiration while preserving the human authors as conscious agents. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The Spirit of God who moved over the waters in creation (Gen 1:2) is the same Spirit who moved through the prophets, revealing the counsel of God to humanity. This establishes the authority of all Old Testament Scripture as originating "from God" (ἀπὸ θεοῦ), not from private human speculation.',
    },
    2: {
        1: 'GREEK: "False teachers" (ψευδοδιδάσκαλοι, pseudodidaskaloi) is a NT hapax legomenon, found only here. "Master" (δεσπότην, despotēn, Strong\'s G1203) denotes absolute ownership, stronger than kyrios—emphasizing Christ\'s sovereign claim over those He purchased (ἀγοράσαντα, agorasanta, "bought," marketplace language). THEOLOGICAL: The denial of Christ\'s lordship is the core heresy; these teachers reject the very One whose redemptive purchase gives Him rightful authority over them (cf. 1 Cor 6:20, Jude 4).',
        4: 'GREEK: "Cast into Tartarus" (ταρταρώσας, tartarōsas) is a NT hapax legomenon (Strong\'s G5020), the only use of this verb in all of Scripture. Tartarus in Greek cosmology was the lowest region of the underworld, beneath Hades. DIVINE_COUNCIL: This refers to the rebellious divine beings of Genesis 6:1-4 and 1 Enoch 6-16, heavenly watchers who transgressed their proper boundary. Peter draws on Second Temple tradition (1 Enoch, Jubilees) where these fallen angels are bound in chains of darkness awaiting final judgment. The "chains of deep darkness" (σειραῖς ζόφου) echo the binding imagery of 1 Enoch 10:4-6.',
        5: 'GREEK: "Herald" (κήρυκα, kēryка, Strong\'s G2783) denotes a public proclaimer or official announcer, not merely a teacher. "Eighth" (ὄγδοον) means Noah plus seven others were preserved. TYPOLOGY: Noah as a preacher of righteousness foreshadows Christ\'s proclamation; the flood as judgment upon the ungodly world prefigures the coming eschatological judgment (cf. Matt 24:37-39, 1 Pet 3:20-21).',
        6: 'GREEK: "Reduced to ashes" (τεφρώσας, tephrōsas) is a NT hapax legomenon, derived from tephra ("ash"). "Example" (ὑπόδειγμα, hypodeigma) indicates Sodom and Gomorrah serve as a visible, historical pattern of divine judgment upon the ungodly. THEOLOGICAL: The destruction functions as a typological warning—what befell these cities foreshadows the eschatological fate of all who practice ungodliness (cf. Jude 7).',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse is the theological conclusion of the extended conditional sentence begun in v. 4. The three historical examples (fallen angels, the flood, Sodom) demonstrate a twofold divine pattern: God simultaneously delivers the godly and reserves the unrighteous for judgment. GREEK: "Under punishment" (κολαζομένους, kolazomenous) is a present passive participle, indicating the unrighteous are presently being punished while being kept for the final day of judgment—an intermediate state of ongoing penalty.',
        10: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Glories" (δόξας, doxas) likely refers to angelic beings or celestial powers, not abstract concepts of glory. These false teachers blaspheme heavenly beings they do not understand. GREEK: "Authority" (κυριότητος, kyriotētos, Strong\'s G2963) may refer to the lordship of Christ or to a class of angelic beings called "dominions" (cf. Eph 1:21, Col 1:16, Jude 8). The parallel with Jude 8-9 strongly supports an angelic referent.',
        15: 'TYPOLOGY: Balaam son of Beor (Num 22-24) is a paradigmatic figure of the prophet-for-hire who leads God\'s people into sin for personal profit. HISTORICAL: "Bosor" is a variant form of "Beor"; some scholars suggest it reflects an Aramaic or Galilean pronunciation. The "way of Balaam" became a standard Jewish and early Christian cipher for those who corrupt the faithful for monetary gain (cf. Num 31:16, Rev 2:14, Jude 11).',
        19: 'GREEK: "Overcome" (ἥττηται, hēttētai, Strong\'s G2274) means to be defeated or made inferior. "Enslaved" (δεδούλωται, dedoulōtai) is a perfect passive, indicating a settled state of bondage. THEOLOGICAL: The grim irony is that these false teachers promise liberty (ἐλευθερίαν) while themselves being slaves of corruption (φθορᾶς). This echoes Jesus\' teaching that everyone who commits sin is a slave of sin (John 8:34).',
        20: 'GREEK: "Full knowledge" (ἐπιγνώσει, epignōsei, Strong\'s G1922) is a strengthened form of gnōsis, denoting thorough, experiential knowledge—not mere acquaintance. "Defilements" (μιάσματα, miasmata) is a NT hapax. THEOLOGICAL: This verse presents one of the most sobering warnings in the NT: those who have come to genuine knowledge of the Lord Jesus Christ and then return to entanglement in worldly corruption are in a worse state than before their knowledge. The passage echoes the Lord\'s teaching in Matt 12:45 and Luke 11:26.',
        22: 'TYPOLOGY: The first proverb echoes Proverbs 26:11 (LXX); the second, about the sow, is not found in the OT and likely derives from extrabiblical tradition, possibly a popular Semitic saying. GREEK: "Wallowing-place" (κυλισμόν, kulismon) is a NT hapax legomenon. THEOLOGICAL: Both images illustrate that the nature of the false teachers has not truly changed—the dog and the sow act according to their nature, returning to filth despite temporary cleansing. This raises profound questions about the genuineness of their earlier profession.',
    },
    3: {
        2: 'GREEK: "Proeirēmenōn" (προειρημένων, from προλέγω, Strong\'s G4302) means "spoken beforehand," emphasizing prophetic foreknowledge. The genitive chain "tēs tōn apostolōn hymōn entolēs tou kyriou kai sōtēros" is complex — the commandment belongs to the Lord and Savior, mediated through the apostles. THEOLOGICAL: Peter places apostolic teaching on par with Old Testament prophetic authority, grounding both in the Lord\'s own word.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: The scoffers\' argument is uniformitarian — "all things continue thus from the beginning of creation" — denying divine intervention in history. This challenges both the Second Coming (parousia) and God\'s sovereign governance of the cosmos. TYPOLOGY: The appeal to "the fathers" falling asleep echoes patriarchal death language (Gen 15:15; Deut 31:16), but the scoffers weaponize it against hope.',
        5: 'GREEK: "Lanthanei" (λανθάνει, Strong\'s G2990) means "it escapes notice" or "is hidden from them," and "thelontas" (θέλοντας) specifies this ignorance is willful — "desiring" it to be so. THEOLOGICAL: Peter refutes uniformitarianism by appealing to creation: the heavens and earth were constituted "out of water and through water by the word of God" (Gen 1:2, 6-9). The same divine word that created can also destroy and remake.',
        6: 'TYPOLOGY: The Flood (Gen 6-9) serves as the decisive counter-example to the scoffers\' claim that God has never intervened catastrophically. "Kataklustheis" (κατακλυσθείς, Strong\'s G2626) is the verbal form behind "cataclysm." The Noahic judgment typologically foreshadows the eschatological judgment by fire (v.7), establishing a pattern: creation, judgment, re-creation.',
        8: 'GREEK: Direct quotation of Psalm 90:4 (LXX 89:4). "Chillia etē" (χίλια ἔτη) = "a thousand years." THEOLOGICAL: Peter does not propose a mathematical formula for calculating the parousia but rather asserts God\'s radical transcendence over time. What appears as delay from a human perspective is not slowness from the divine perspective. This verse became foundational for later millennial discussions.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Makrothymei" (μακροθυμεῖ, Strong\'s G3114) — "is longsuffering" — reframes apparent delay as merciful patience. The divine will is expressed in two complementary purposes: "not willing that any should perish" and "that all should come to repentance" (metanoian, μετάνοιαν). GREEK: "Boulomenos" (βουλόμενος, Strong\'s G1014) denotes deliberate intention or counsel, not mere wish — God\'s patience is purposeful and salvific.',
        10: 'GREEK: "Rhoizēdon" (ῥοιζηδόν, Strong\'s G4500) is a hapax legomenon in the NT — occurring only here — meaning "with a rushing noise" or "with a great roar," an onomatopoeic term evoking the violent sound of cosmic dissolution. "Stoicheia" (στοιχεῖα, Strong\'s G4747) may denote elemental substances or cosmic powers. TYPOLOGY: "The day of the Lord" echoes the prophetic yom YHWH tradition (Isa 13:6; Joel 2:1; Amos 5:18), now applied to Christ\'s return.',
        13: 'TYPOLOGY: "New heavens and a new earth" directly echoes Isaiah 65:17 and 66:22 (LXX), the prophetic promise of cosmic renewal. "Kainos" (καινός, Strong\'s G2537) denotes qualitative newness — not merely another cosmos but a transformed one. THEOLOGICAL: "In which righteousness dwells" (dikaiosynē katoikei) indicates not merely the absence of sin but the permanent habitation of divine justice — the telos of redemption.',
        15: 'HISTORICAL: Peter\'s reference to Paul as "our beloved brother" and to "the wisdom given to him" is remarkable — it acknowledges Paul\'s apostolic authority while placing his letters alongside authoritative teaching. This is one of the earliest attestations of a Pauline letter collection. THEOLOGICAL: "Count the longsuffering of our Lord as salvation" links back to v.9, interpreting divine patience through a soteriological lens.',
        16: 'GREEK: "Dysnóēta" (δυσνόητα, Strong\'s G1425) — "hard to understand" — is a hapax legomenon in the NT. "Strebloōsin" (στρεβλοῦσιν, Strong\'s G4761) means "to twist" or "to distort," used of torture on the rack — a violent metaphor for mishandling Scripture. THEOLOGICAL: Peter explicitly categorizes Paul\'s letters alongside "the rest of the Scriptures" (tas loipas graphas), an extraordinary early witness to the emerging canonical status of apostolic writings.',
        18: 'GREEK: "Auxanete" (αὐξάνετε, Strong\'s G837) is present imperative — "keep on growing." THEOLOGICAL: The doxology "to him be the glory both now and unto the day of eternity" ascribes to Christ the glory that belongs to God alone, a profound Christological affirmation. "Hēmeran aiōnos" (ἡμέραν αἰῶνος) — "the day of eternity" — is a striking phrase blending temporal and eternal categories, pointing to the consummation when time yields to everlasting reality.',
    },
}